segments.text: We had at that point in a very quick period, less than 120 days, the capability to do planning a la Florida or any other mandatory planning state.
That's what we're embroiled in now, trying to educate the people involved in the system.
It's hard to get everybody up to speed as to what that means.
We're so used to zoning being planning around this part of the world that it's taken a massive educational participatory structure.
We could have as professionals prepared a plan, but it won't work in Austin.
And a mandatory plan would not work unless there was a very massive and structured way

educate people on the relationships between planning, regulation, the consistency doctrine, adequate service and facilities ordinances, and all the kinds of techniques of planning and growth management as I believe in them.
Let's talk about the consistency doctrine for a minute.
I don't know where that term doctrine appeared.
And I'm not even sure if it is a doctrine.
And I don't think it's been pinned on anyone yet.
But it does remind me of Oregon and the mandated planning procedures in Oregon.
And all of their, quote, acknowledged, unquote, plans that have to be promulgated by cities as well as counties.
And that if they don't act accordingly, then they're open to lawsuits.
Right.
The question then is, when is zoning and other development action considered to be consistent with an adopted comprehensive plan?
And what constitutes consistency?
What about the time lag between short-range and medium-range and long-range?
These are questions that I don't find adequately answered in the literature.
Well, I tend to agree with that.
There's kind of two ways to talk about consistency.
My first bath in consistency came from what I was seeing happen in California, perhaps Oregon also, but I didn't follow the Oregon system that well.
But I was repeatedly told by peers at conferences, just in general networking talk and discussion over a few years, that consistency had become interpreted in California
Your document had to be internally consistent, you know, one policy among another, water to sewer to wastewater to parks, all that kind of, that's very logical to understand.
The plan should be internally consistent, very rational approach.
But what was coming out of some of the mandatory plan litigation in California
was that you were getting lawsuits by either the developer or the neighborhood or the environmentalist challenging legislative decisions not being consistent with their plan.
Well, that was kind of a new phenomenon.
I haven't talked about 10 or 15 years ago even.
That was kind of a new phenomenon when you're challenging zoning.
You don't challenge planning.
You accept the absence of it, perhaps.
And just following that whole discussion over a period of months and years that
that people could actually overturn a zoning decision because they found a council did not follow their plan.
Or even better, that a developer could get his denial overturned because the council had ignored its plan that said he could do that, or something to that effect.
I mean, the two-edged sword of the consistency doctrine I found very, very interesting.
The issue of timing.
became very focused in Florida when the legislation there is replete with consistency requirements.

In Broward County, where I spent my sojourn, the interpretation in Broward County by the county commission and their plan, which ruled over 29 cities as well as all the unincorporated jurisdiction down there, was you brought your plan
and your zoning consistent within one year.
Within one year?
Because Florida statutes required in a little phrase that zoning shall be consistent with a plan within one year of its amendment.
Well, they used that to say if we plan the reaches of the county to have commercial out here 20 years from now, you go ahead and zone it now.
Now, that was a...
And we spent one of our whole continuing processes was staff initiated zoning to conformity.
We were continuously preparing studies, initiating county commission rezonings to consistency so the zoning map would look like plan map.
And that is a problem.
Now, that's a problem that I've had to deal with in other

arenas as we moved into the land development code regulatory systems the impact fee systems which i've had considerable experience with because the timing of adequacy and the delivery of services and the moratorium that's implied if services aren't adequate you cannot in the consistency doctorate grant the project on the other hand if you find those searches adequate
or pay an impact fee, you can approve the project.
That didn't get at the timing issue, but it got at an issue about what is a plan.
How can you make a roadway consistent with a plan in the future when we know zoning traditionally is planning?
So you may show it on a map today and plan a road for it, but what really going to be out there 10 or 15 years from now
may not equal the capacity that you've built into your roads and all that.
So I've dealt with that.
And I have a style of planning theory we're going to try to embed in the Austin plans, comprehensive land use element, that I think bridges that gap.
And it's not mapping the multicolored yellows, reds for residential and commercial in the traditional sense that you'd have to say, well, that's commercial, so zone it today.
I don't believe in that one-to-one correlation.
I believe in the timing, long range, and short range.
But I have a different value and a different philosophy of what the land use plan should be.
The land use element of the comprehensive plan.
It shouldn't just be a surrogate zoning map.
And that's what it's traditionally been.
Well, that's what it's been in Texas as well as other states.
And going way back to the model land use planning,
act of the Department of Commerce with Secretary Hoover and the consequences of confusion that that generated in the planning profession for decades.
The planners themselves got confused between the land use element and the zoning ordinance.
For example, Harlem Bartholomew would from time to time insert a zoning ordinance into his
plan documents for various communities, thinking that that would take care of land use.
We've not entirely emerged from that, I suspect.
No, no.
And see, it's that whole philosophy that made me skeptical about coming back to this part of the world again.
Well, Norman, I'd like to have you elucidate on your concepts of what comprehensive plans
is and how it relates to implementation devices.
Well, we are working on a report here to go to our land use task group, part of our big participatory structure that's involved in the Austin plan process.
How many are in that?
Well, there's 87 officially appointed council representatives representing nine

political interests in the community they are decomposed into 14 various task groups working on water wastewater environment land development code house you know all the elements of the plan okay is it and they have appointed on to the you know six or eight of each of those are on one of these task groups then from the bottom up there's other resource
people, board and commission members, so you flesh out about 20, 30 people in any one of these groups.
I see.
It's very elaborate.
We can give you the process document, how these things operate.
How many, is there any geographic representation by neighborhood?
Yes, yes.
They've got the largest block of representatives in the process.
That's similar to the Austin Tomorrow process.
Similar, but different.
Because what's different about it, it does have a broad vested interest representation from not just the neighborhoods and environmentalists, which I have been told Austin-Tamara deteriorated into.
The big hitters pulled out of the process and went on and started doing muds.
And so for whatever reason, I think this has...
The whole thrust of our participatory structure is to reach consensus among the groups that have never sat down and talked to each other.
So it's hopefully balanced to do that.
That's the question that's still out there.
OK. What about your concept of the content of a comprehensive plan for us?
Well, I truly believe it needs to be a public goals policy document.
although it's going to be a very thick document, I think.
Will it be a general plan or will it be more or less of a development plan?
It's going to be a hybrid.
A hybrid.
It's going to look somewhat traditional and it's going to look rather innovative in some respects, I hope.
Let me back up and tell you what I think the key is that I hope to embed in the thing if I have any influence on it.
If you take a traditional land use map, multi-colored map, you pull out and fold out of tons of plants.
They're generalized, you know, red commercial here, gray industry here, green for parks, whatever the color coding system is.
The art and science of planters
pushing those blobs around on the map and having them mean anything quantifiably is rather lacking.
We do acreage and absorptions and projections, whatever techniques are used.
They're pretty sad, in my opinion.
They're good, reasonable estimates, perhaps.
They represent community beliefs about this is good, we ought to have this here or that there.
What we really do, though, is back off in the regulatory system
And right ordinances don't have a damn thing to do with reaching those goals.
They have more to do with whatever the political issue is, an environmental problem, or right of watershed ordinance, or got a problem with signs, right of sign ordinance.
But that has no correlation, really, with achieving the objective of the city looking like that 20 years from now.
And there's not that good a tie to making sure that capital investment
is being timed and sequenced to make that plan, because that plan is too general, perhaps.
But if you take that red map and that green map and that yellow map, my philosophy of how you bridge this system is to quantify those blobs in a relationship way.
And we've got a rather lengthy report that we're going to be bringing out here in the next 90 days or so.
In a manner that does not try to predict
the use of every parcel of property in the planning sphere of jurisdiction in a sense that it's all at this corner going to be red or green or blue or whatever the color might be.
But to have those designations on your plan map represent planned impact or intensity levels
which we have done quite a bit of research and coming all the way out of our impact analysis basis in Florida.
We've set up a system that starts very simply.
The single family unit equivalent is not a particularly new idea.
But rather than saying this land supports three to five single family units, we would say this has a single family unit equivalent
intensity value.
And we also have a scale in there that says one single family unit is the same as .8 townhouses or .3 duplexes.
They're all related across a scale of traffic impacts initially.
Then quantifiable charts and tables about water quality and water quantity and sewage quantity and all these, you know, rather rigorous
You've got a size for water and sewer.
They're impact-related equivalents.
Now, you can bifurcate one of those districts.
You could say everything is equivalent from a traffic point of view and just have one blob on your mat wouldn't tell you a thing.
But where you want higher intensity, you'll raise the FAR and scale up intensities.
We have a corollary set of value systems that relate

square footage of office, to square footages of industry, to square footages of discrete use types, so that we know that the same amount of office space in any particular zoning category will have the same impact.
So what we're trying to plan is the probable future impact, not the probable zoning that's going to happen there.
But in a mandatory plan system, we'll let zoning take its place over time as market dictates.
You've got an intensity level.

that might permit X quantity of office, a little less quantity of retail, same traffic impact, you may choose in that district to convert to high-rise apartments equivalent to the same traffic impact.
It's that kind of dimension we're starting to explore.
Now, you are assuming that the traffic impacts are going to remain constant from current phenomenon?
It's all predicated on, right now, very traditional relationships like an ITE schedule, you know, that says a house generates 0.76 trips per day.
peak hour or 10 trips per 80.
It's a beginning generalization.
I don't care.
You could change that mix any way you want to.
I'm not trying to make it mathematically perfect.
I'm trying to say let's not predict this is going to be retail and have no way to know how much retail is going to be there.
We're going to fix retail in the plan at an intensity, at an FAR level.
But we're not going to say that's all it can be there.
There could be apartments there of the same relative impact.
When you say impact, you're talking about traffic generation impact?
Starting first from a traffic generation point of view.
We've had a number of discussions with various members of the Planning Commission and others who think, well, that's ridiculous.
There's other impacts.
Why don't you do a multivariate?
We squish it all up.
You can't get to the point of quantifying that use
and put it right into your traffic model.
You can't quantify those uses and size of water line if you've made them all surrogates.
You have to start with one dimension.
What's the most serious dimension of public service?
In my opinion, in 22 years, it's roads and traffic.
Such an enormous lead time, such a massive amount of land to acquire, and the greatest capital cost,
Your roads are fairly going to be fixed.
The only question is how large they need to be and can you regulate through a plan land use intensities that will never exceed that planned roadway capacity.
Yeah, you can under a system like we're talking about.
You can't under the two-dimensional traditional multicolored land use map.
So that's the, you may disagree, but that's the direction we believe we're taking because it takes you then from a mandatory impact planning system

to a flexible zoning system you can make regulations do what regulation ought to do policy decisions in the plan right now every zoning decision it's immaterial what the requirements of the zoning ordinance are it's an original decision by city council where that's good at that location you know it's planning by individual ad hoc case well
This is interesting for me to hear this because when I started planning, there were no such things as tables of traffic generation factors.
We had to conduct our own field research.
Absolutely.
And we need to do that today.
Yeah, we need to update it.
We need to do a lot of that kind of stuff.
We need to localize and do, in my opinion, we need to have the capability
to replicate ITE tables here on a biannual or quarterly basis.
Or just say, hey, it was changing in Austin Texas.
I mean, our phenomena are not the same as they are in Washington DC.
But it wouldn't take much to do this just on a spot survey basis during different times of the year and so forth.
But all I'm saying, we're trying to develop a planning mapped mandatory land use system that gives you a capability

If this is the consensus of what this community today wants this city to be, high intensity here, low intensity there, traditional neighborhoods here, transit corridor station locations for light rail here, we're going to fix those in relative quantity in plan.
You're not going to exceed these.
Now, you can move across the variety of mix from retail to industry to housing at the zoning change time, the compatibility time,

20 years from now but we can plan now the roadway system if you achieve the upper limit that will be satisfactory and then we can back down and we can also stepwise figure of all the potential uses in there which one's the most water demanding which one's the most sewer demanding and back into a planning methodology it can it can be automated quite frankly oh yeah
And as you make planning amendments from year to year or however, you can also produce it now needs to amend the roadway.
If you want to change the plan and up the density, the consistency doctrine tells me I got to go back and change the roadway plan.
I got to change the water plan.
I got to add more parks.
And you do what planners have always been wanting to do, relate facilities to planning, adequate services.
That's my latest.
I'm out of the impact fee game, and I'm into the planning impact.
And to show to the commission and the council what the consequences would be of making these decisions.
Absolutely.
I don't care personally as a planner to tell a community, this should be a commercial shopping center, this should be a nine-story high-rise.
No, cut it to six.
I don't like the zoning game.
This community needs to decide what it wants to be.
If it wants to change that, we need to be able to show them
Don't just change that zoning without knowing that you're going to have such congestion here and the consistency doctrine requires you to find a way to change immediately the roadway plan.
We're going to make decision making, make some tough choices in the future instead of just playing with the old traditional game.
That's a pretty tough agenda.
It is.
And nobody knows that's the agenda here.
Except me.
But I believe that's what the public wants out of its governmental decision-making systems.
Well, I think that they also want something more than that, Norman.
I think that they want professional judgments to be exercised in terms of recommendations to the city through the council and the commission regarding the location of activities.
Sure.
And I think that role is constant in the evolution and the assistance and the preparation of the plan, the staffing of the regulations, the staffing of the...
I mean, it never ends there.
It's bound to be.
But what we have, if we have a planning system that's theoretically perfect, is what I'm talking about, we have that impermanent constitution that planning has always been alleged to be.
It's that backdrop against...
Make the decisions in relationship to your plan.
This plan is what it is today.
It's going to change.
Economic conditions are going to change.
ITEs are going to change.
Cars are going to change.
Travel patterns are going to change.
We can change the plan.
And we can change the plan consistently to respond to public policy by the vote of the council to change that plan.
Do you have in mind, after adoption,
and you go into the next phase after adoption, do you have in mind anything like annual review and update?
Absolutely.
As a matter of fact, our charter stipulates that there will be, didn't set the period, but they said there'll be monitoring and at least, I think it says in there, five-year periodic major review.
Yeah, that's excellent.
We had in Florida, in the Breyer County system, we had a system of one-year plan amendments.
If your zoning wasn't consistent, you got denied.
You could file for a plan amendment and wait for it to cycle up.
And what you did is we took large planning areas, got all plan amendments in, held one staff report public hearing on all of those, and you amended the plan at one time or didn't amend it or didn't.
But it was done in a comprehensive basis.
We have weekly rezonings in College State.
Oh, I know that.
But that's because zoning is planning in Texas.
You know what I mean?
Oh, of course I know.

What I wanted to ask you, what would be a neat trick would be if you could schedule those annual updates so that they would be ready and completed in time for the city manager to use them as a basis for formulating his annual budget.
Oh, no question about it.
As a matter of fact, we've already talked about linking our annexation program, our capital budgeting program, backing it all up in the process.
So all these things happen prior to the operating budget cycle.
I mean, there's so much depending upon that.
Then that would put planning in a leadership role.
Well, it certainly... Rather than a reactive role.
Absolutely.
It would put it at the right arm of...
municipal management in an intelligent management function where it should be.
Right.
Part of a city administration.
Not just another line operation down there to implement something.
Well, I think that the tie between city administration and city planning is long overdue to be strengthened.
And managers, if they have a good planning director who is sympathetic to this as well,
can realize that planning can be an enormous tool for it.
I know.
You hear that said by city managers every time they speak at conferences.
But you don't hear city managers speak like that to city managers at the ICMA conference.
You don't.
City managers are politically pragmatic beasts.
They know where.
the zoning case is, and they know who owns the land, and they live in that arena of politics.
And in short range.
And it's just as short range as the people who hire them.
And the planter forever is caught in a box, in my opinion, except I've had the rare privilege of working for a few city managers that do meet the mold.
Well, Lloyd Cookingham in Kansas City was probably the best example of a city manager that understood the potential relationship between the planning process and city management.
But there aren't a whole lot of Cookinghams around.
Yeah.
Well, I totally agree.
Norman, the timing on the Austin Plan project.
Would you go through the major points in time you anticipated?
Sure.
It was a consciously conceived program designed to take approximately two years.

It took about six months longer to get initiated than we had planned on because of change in council election, the whole timing of the thing, and the need for the new council to just get up to speed with their job before they got on with it.
the process of appointments.
Council elections came in the middle of trying to get this process started.

So it wasn't until almost a year after council elections in 85 that they finished all the appointments and we officially kicked the process off with a big meeting out at one of the hotels and started all that formal deliberation.
We're now... Has the change in the council had any consequences for the program?
Only that hiatus, slow down period, it put it behind schedule in my mind, probably six months.

But you have, in my opinion, you have to give a lot more credit than people are willing to do to the original Mullen Council, the perceived developer controlled council, in which all of this took place.
Northwest Plan, the Charter Amendment.
A lot of things took place in an era under a council that was perceived to be anti-neighborhood, pro-development.
Some people say, well, they were just doing that because of the enormous visibility in the upcoming elections.
They were playing to the pro-planning neighborhood mood and then got swept out of office anyway.
I don't know whether that's true, but...

The new council is not, well, it just took longer to get up to speed with them, and they are so slow to make decisions, I mean, any decision out there, so it's a different council, but still it's a very supportive council, I mean, to say that.
Anyway, we're about nine months into the process.
I've alluded to the structure of appointees and task groups supported by
staff, the relevant departments, planning's lead agency, and all these various elements groups.
We have a definite process that results in three milestone reports.
The first milestone is basically, and all groups are through that process now, is basically an issue definition.
You have to understand, we've got the developers and the environmentalists and the Hispanics and the blacks.
We've got all the communities sitting there trying to figure out what's common, what's good, what's bad, and come up with eventually the goals and policies in a consensus-making process.
Is this report available now?
reports that thick.
I mean, just tons of them.
We don't tell you.
You get buried trying to read all of them.
It's not important for this project or my project.
So the first milestone is basically a process of getting people to work together.
We have facilitators, professional facilitators who live in Austin, volunteer services, tons.
I mean, night meetings.
You know the process is night meetings out at the wazoo.
So the first several months was a getting to know each other, getting testing ground among the battling constituent groups, a beginning to deal with what do you think the problems of Austin are.
The second milestone, which they're all beginning to approach now, deals with the definition of these are our values.
The first milestone was issues and values.
trying to get them to focus.
Now, what are our goals and objectives and probable ways to implement those?
Each one of these kind of bleeds across.
You can finish it if you can get there, or you can carry it over.
So now we're beginning to take those values and problems and define their goal sets, what they think Austin's vision ought to be, and all this kind of thing.
move as far down that goals, policies, objectives, and standards as they can.
You've got a housing task group doing this.
You've got water and wastewater.
You've got all the element groups, all dealing with this public policy and decision consensus piece up front.
Then when they get through that process, they'll go to milestone three, which is implementation.

techniques and strategies and ordinance requirements and the teeth of all that you'll have basically a whole superstructure of consensus agreement about issues values goals policies objectives standards and the tools and of course you got a land use group doing you know their piece on this evolving this consensus of austin's vision
of what they want this city to be, how they wanted to get there, the standards that they want this city to be.
You know, they'll cover all the issues.

At that point, as they wrap up their individual third milestones, we take each of those elements, and they're staggered over three and four month periods, into the superstructure of the ordinance mandated by the Charter, the Comprehensive Plan Ordinance.
And it'll be kind of a chapter by chapter thing.
And we will adopt the housing component of the plan.
And then we'll adopt whatever else comes on stream.
All designed to be an interim document.
All the interdependencies, just like any other ordinance.
If wastewater comes on and says, you got something there that doesn't work, we work it out and then we adopt it.
Two of them updated.
We strike old language, so both those are compatible.
Internal consistency piece.
And every element comes on and is adjudicated to be... And finally you come out with this plan.
This is a first test.
But you'll go through a series of interim element adoptions.
And then this will eventually yield the comprehensive plan.
The final total plan.
With plan diagrams and all that.
Yes, and you will have the birth.
of the comprehensive plan.
And you know from there it's annual revisions, articulations, refinements, changes, and modifications.
At least we have that coherent document to start with.
So that you're really, when you say an interim plan element is going to be adopted, I think if I'm interpreting this correctly, what this means
then is that what you're doing is it's sort of like a sketch plan, and you're going to use this for testing and adjustment with other elements so that it can be brought into balance.
And then all of those then would, you're not really going into piecemeal adoption as such.
Well, there's some debates whether if that might happen.
It might happen more in terms of adopting a sectors land use plan.
You better talk to Alfred Bettman.
He'll have some things to say about that, and so would Ladislaus Segal.
I understand that.
But this is based upon Austin's traditional bias for action.
Unquote.
But, Norman, still one could say, I think...
It's not inconceivable that you could do a housing element
with goals and policies and objectives and standards and implementation programs that could be adopted.
There's not a lot that will not have happened in all the interdependencies and internal consistency of time they get there to preclude that from happening.
Some of the more intricate ones, land use to transportation, land use to water, some of the superstructure things,
probably can't just be done in a bag.
That's what I was going to say.
I think that your three mandated elements probably would have to be adopted simultaneously.
Oh, no question.
And also, the whole process was designed to bring on land use, housing, and infrastructure.
That's an important thing to understand.
Sure.
And the process of who got started when has to do with that.
Oh, yeah.
Of course, and then, of course, if you were on the Gulf, you could have a port element or whatever, but that could come years later.
Sure, absolutely.
And it could come about as political pressures generated.
Absolutely, and our charter provides that.
Well, in that sense, it could be piecemeal, and in that sense, it could be very realistic in terms of relating or planning to the decision process.
Well, I think it's very interesting, and I certainly wish you a whole bunch of success on it.
Well, we need a whole bunch of support now.
It's a novel thing.
Try to attempt this.
Well, Austin is a tough city for planners.
Unlike any place I've ever worked in 22 years, it is novel, to say the least.
Are there any other things you would
Well, did we ever get to the end of when the comprehensive plan might be adopted?
The mandate in the mission statement given to this community participation group was to have a plan for adoption by within 24 months, which puts it out in like February, March of 88.
And right now,
Unbelievable.
We're on schedule.
We had this thing purged out, and we're on schedule, relatively speaking.
Of course, we haven't got to any real tough inter-group conflicts yet, because it's all still been at the pretty general theoretical testing level.
I think that two years for the formulation of a
Any comprehensive plan, let alone something that has a lot of new approaches in it, is probably minimum.
Oh, I guarantee you it's minimum.
I was one of three.
Yeah, I would be more comfortable with three.
But pragmatic politics and a city manager and others said no way.
And that's always there.
Yeah.
But the manager is very protective, I hope, of the comprehensive planning process and not getting it mixed up with day-to-day planning.
Yes, and actually the organization of the two departments is by that very design.
The day-to-day stuff, the zoning, the regulatory, the site plans, the building permits and all that are all over the land development services and all that kind of stuff.
We're over here doing the plan.

annexation we've got some routine stuff and basically the whole man-based information system multi-departmental computer operation i think it's interesting that you're physically at some distance from the rest of the city well it's not by desire but
There's no city hall building that, you know, there's just not a capability to put people together.
We've got pretty quality space.
Actually, I like being removed from the hectics of that process.
There are real needs for us to talk daily, and we do.
Jim Duncan and I.
This process would not work if there weren't two people as compatible as Jim Duncan and I running current and long-range planning, in fact.
because so much of what they do has to just do this eventually.
And if you had two competing egos about philosophies that didn't go down the same track, I mean, it's bad enough to work with the various departments and the turfing issues you have in any city.
Sure.
Now, when we finish this process, we need to put the two departments back together.
Probably so.
Jim, I want to... Jim...
Norman, I want to thank you very much for your time and for all of the very interesting ideas.
I certainly wish you well.
